\newlabel{fig:qual}{{2}{8}{\textbf {WILT elicits the behaviour in a fluent, on-scenario response; every baseline misses it, degenerates, drifts off-scenario, or sounds contrived.} Illustrative target responses for one scenario. BoN stays on-policy but does not elicit; W2S elicits yet collapses into a high-probability degenerate loop (low naturalness); BEAST's gibberish input leaves the target confused and off-scenario; FLRT stays fluent but drifts to an unrelated topic; G-PAIR elicits only through a contrived role-play framing}{figure.caption.3}{}}
\newlabel{fig:qual@cref}{{[figure][2][]2}{[1][7][]8}{}{}{}}
\newlabel{tab:ablations}{{2}{8}{\textbf {Every part of WILT pulls its weight: removing any one lowers behaviour presence, naturalness, or output probability.} Each row removes or swaps a single component of WILT (\cref {sec:method}), holding the rest fixed; metrics as in \cref {sec:experiments}. The last row replaces self-corruption with a separate W2S proxy pair}{table.caption.4}{}}
